How to Create a Number Guessing Game in C
This article will walk you through the process of creating a simple number guessing game in C.

Step 1: Define the Rules
Before you begin writing the code, it's important to clearly define the rules of the game. Here are the rules for our number guessing game:

- The player will guess a number between 1 and 100.
- If the player guesses the number correctly, they will win the game.
- If the player guesses the number incorrectly, the game will end and the player will have to start over.

Step 2: Define the Variables
Now that the rules have been defined, we need to create some variables to store the number and the player's guesses. We'll create two variables, num and guess, and assign them the types int and char, respectively.

int num;
char guess;

Step 3: Display the Rules
Use the following code to display the rules of the game to the player:

printf("Guess a number between 1 and 100.\n");
printf("Enter your guess: ");
scanf("%c", &guess);

Step 4: Check the Guess
Use the following code to check if the player's guess is correct:

if (guess == num) {
  printf("Yes, the number is %d.\n", num);
} else {
  printf("No, the number is not %d.\n", num);
}

Step 5: End the Game
Use the following code to end the game and allow the player to start over:

printf("Press any key to restart the game.\n");
getchar();

Step 6: Run the Game
Now that the code has been written, it's time to run the game. First, make sure that you have a C compiler and development environment installed on your computer. Then, compile and run the game using the appropriate commands for your compiler.

When you run the game, it will display the rules and prompt you to guess a number. You can then enter your guess and the game will check to see if you are correct. If you are correct, the game will display a message telling you so, and you can press any key to start over. If you are incorrect, the game will display a message telling you so, and you will have to guess again.

 This tutorial will focus on Microsoft Visual Studios Professional 2013, but the code will work on any program in any edition.;
